{"timestamp":"2026-02-10T02:14:06.388Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"call_OxdXPg4Hs5CyVVekBbFpHVU3","output":"Chunk ID: 97f60a\nWall time: 0.0504 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 11361\nOutput:\nTotal output lines: 624\n\n# Feature Specification: UC-Driven Specification & Unified UAT\n\n**Feature Branch**: `[001-uc-spec-union]`  \n**Created**: 2026-02-10  \n**Status**: Draft  \n**Input**: User description: \"Use cases for this project are provided as Markdown files in the project directory, with file names of the form UC-XX.md, where XX is a one digit or two digit number. Create the specification using these files, and capturing all elements of each use case. Acceptance test suites for UC-XX.md are designed in TC-XX.md. You will create a user acceptance test suite that is the union of all use case acceptance test suites.\"\n\n## Scope\n\nThis specification covers all functional behavior described in UC-01 through\nUC-29 and all acceptance tests described in TC-01 through TC-29. Anything not\nrepresented in these files is out of scope.\n\n## User Scenarios & Testing *(mandatory)*\n\n### User Story 1 - UC-01 - View Public Announcements (Priority: P3)\n\nAllow an unregistered user to view conference-related announcements without requiring authentication. (Primary actor: Public User (Guest); Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The guest navigates to the CMS website or selects the announcements section..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Supports informational access; can follow core operational flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: Public announcements are successfully retrieved and displayed to the guest.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The CMS web application is deployed and accessible via a supported web browser.; Public announcements have been created and stored in the CMS database., **When** The guest navigates to the CMS website or selects the announcements section., **Then** Public announcements are successfully retrieved and displayed to the guest.\n2. **Given** 3a**: No public announcements exist, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 2 - UC-02 - View Conference Registration Prices (Priority: P3)\n\nAllow a guest user to view the conference registration price list without registering or logging into the system. (Primary actor: Public User (Guest); Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The guest navigates to the registration or pricing section of the CMS website..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Supports informational access; can follow core operational flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The conference registration price list is successfully displayed to the guest.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The CMS web application is deployed and accessible via a supported web browser.; The conference registration price list has been defined and stored in the CMS., **When** The guest navigates to the registration or pricing section of the CMS website., **Then** The conference registration price list is successfully displayed to the guest.\n2. **Given** 4a**: Registration price list is not available, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 3 - UC-03 - View Conference Schedule (Priority: P3)\n\nAllow a guest user to view the published conference schedule without registering or logging into the system. (Primary actor: Public User (Guest); Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The guest navigates to the conference schedule section of the CMS website..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Supports informational access; can follow core operational flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The published conference schedule is successfully displayed to the guest.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The CMS web application is deployed and accessible via a supported web browser.; A final conference schedule has been generated and published in the CMS., **When** The guest navigates to the conference schedule section of the CMS website., **Then** The published conference schedule is successfully displayed to the guest.\n2. **Given** 4a**: Conference schedule has not been published, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 4 - UC-04 - Register User Account (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow a new user to create a CMS account using a unique and valid email address in order to access system features. (Primary actor: Registered User (new user); Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database Email Validation Service; Trigger: The user selects the ‚ÄúRegister‚Äù option on the CMS website..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: A new user account is successfully created and stored in the CMS database, and the user is redirected to the login page.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The CMS web application is accessible via a supported web browser.; The user does not already have an account with the same email address., **When** The user selects the ‚ÄúRegister‚Äù option on the CMS website., **Then** A new user account is successfully created and stored in the CMS database, and the user is redirected to the login page.\n2. **Given** 6a**: Email format is invalid, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 5 - UC-05 - Validate Registration Information (Priority: P2)\n\nEnsure that all user-provided registration information is valid, complete, and secure before creating a user account. (Primary actor: Registered User (new user during registration); Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database Validation Service; Trigger: The user submits the registration form..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The user‚Äôs registration information is validated successfully, allowing the account creation process to continue.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The CMS registration form is accessible.; The user has entered registration information into the form.; The CMS validation mechanisms are operational., **When** The user submits the registration form., **Then** The user‚Äôs registration information is validated successfully, allowing the account creation process to continue.\n2. **Given** 3a**: Email format is invalid, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 6 - UC-06 - Log In to System (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow a registered user to authenticate using valid credentials in order to access their personalized dashboard and system features. (Primary actor: Registered User; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database Authentication Service; Trigger: The user selects the ‚ÄúLog In‚Äù option on the CMS website..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: The user is successfully authenticated and redirected to their personalized dashboard.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The user has previously registered an account in the CMS.; The CMS web application is accessible via a supported web browser., **When** The user selects the ‚ÄúLog In‚Äù option on the CMS website., **Then** The user is successfully authenticated and redirected to their personalized dashboard.\n2. **Given** 5a**: Username or password is incorrect, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 7 - UC-07 - Change Password (Priority: P2)\n\nAllow a registered user to securely change their account password in order to maintain or restore account security. (Primary actor: Registered User; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database Authentication Service; Trigger: The user selects the ‚ÄúChange Password‚Äù option from their account or profile settings..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The user‚Äôs password is successfully updated in the CMS database, and the new password is required for future logins.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The user is registered in the CMS.; The user is authenticated and logged into the CMS.; The CMS password management functionality is available., **When** The user selects the ‚ÄúChange Password‚Äù option from their account or profile settings., **Then** The user‚Äôs password is successfully updated in the CMS database, and the new password is required for future logins.\n2. **Given** The user‚Äôs password is not changed, and the original password remains valid., **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 8 - UC-08 - Submit Paper Manuscript (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow an author to submit a complete paper manuscript and required metadata so that the paper enters the conference review process. (Primary actor: Author; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database File Storage System; Trigger: The author selects the ‚ÄúSubmit Paper‚Äù option from their dashboard..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: The paper manuscript and all required submission information are successfully stored and marked as submitted for review.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The author is registered in the CMS.; The author is authenticated and logged into the CMS.; The paper submission feature is currently available., **When** The author selects the ‚ÄúSubmit Paper‚Äù option from their dashboard., **Then** The paper manuscript and all required submission information are successfully stored and marked as submitted for review.\n2. **Given** 5a**: Uploaded file format is not supported, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 9 - UC-09 - Upload Manuscript File (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow an author to upload a manuscript file that complies with the conference‚Äôs format and size requirements so it can be included in a paper submission. (Primary actor: Author; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database File Storage System; Trigger: The author selects the option to upload a manuscript file during the paper submission process..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: The manuscript file is successfully validated, stored, and associated with the author‚Äôs paper submission.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The author is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; The author has initiated a paper submission.; The CMS file upload functionality is available., **When** The author selects the option to upload a manuscript file during the paper submission process., **Then** The manuscript file is successfully validated, stored, and associated with the author‚Äôs paper submission.\n2. **Given** 5a**: File format is not supported, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 10 - UC-10 - Save Submission Progress (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow an author to save a partially completed paper submission so that the submission can be resumed at a later time without loss of data. (Primary actor: Author; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The author selects the ‚ÄúSave‚Äù option during the paper submission process..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: The current state of the paper submission is successfully stored and can be retrieved later by the author.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The author is registered in the CMS.; The author is authenticated and logged into the CMS.; The author has initiated a paper submission.; The CMS submission-saving functionality is available., **When** The author selects the ‚ÄúSave‚Äù option during the paper submission process., **Then** The current state of the paper submission is successfully stored and can be retrieved later by the author.\n2. **Given** 3a**: Submission data contains invalid or incomplete values, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 11 - UC-11 - Receive Paper Decision (Priority: P2)\n\nInform an author of the final acceptance or rejection decision for a submitted paper once the review process is complete. (Primary actor: Author; Secondary actors: Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database Notification Service (e.g., email); Trigger: The editor records the final decision for a paper after all required reviews are completed..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The author successfully receives and can view the final decision (accept or reject) for their paper.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The author has submitted a paper to the CMS.; All required reviews for the paper have been completed.; The editor has finalized and saved the decision.; The CMS notification and viewing mechanisms are available., **When** The editor records the final decision for a paper after all required reviews are completed., **Then** The author successfully receives and can view the final decision (accept or reject) for their paper.\n2. **Given** 3a**: Notification delivery fails, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 12 - UC-12 - Receive Presentation Schedule (Priority: P2)\n\nInform an author of the finalized presentation time and location for their accepted paper so they can informing plan and prepare for the conference. (Primary actor: Author; Secondary actors: Administrator Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database Notification Service (e.g., email); Trigger: The conference schedule is finalized and published by the administrator or editor..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The author successfully receives and can view the presentation schedule details for their accepted paper.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The author has submitted a paper to the CMS.; The paper has been accepted.; The conference schedule has been generated and finalized.; The CMS schedule publication and notification mechanisms are available., **When** The conference schedule is finalized and published by the administrator or editor., **Then** The author successfully receives and can view the presentation schedule details for their accepted paper.\n2. **Given** 3a**: Notification delivery fails, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 13 - UC-13 - Receive Review Invitation (Priority: P2)\n\nNotify a referee that they have been invited to review a submitted paper so they can decide whether to accept or decline the review assignment. (Primary actor: Referee; Secondary actors: Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database Notification Service (e.g., email); Trigger: The editor assigns a referee to a submitted paper..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The referee successfully receives a review invitation and can view the paper details and respond to the invitation.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The referee is registered in the CMS.; The editor has initiated referee assignment for a submitted paper.; The referee has not exceeded the maximum allowed number of assigned papers.; The CMS notification mechanism is available., **When** The editor assigns a referee to a submitted paper., **Then** The referee successfully receives a review invitation and can view the paper details and respond to the invitation.\n2. **Given** 3a**: Referee has reached the maximum allowed number of review assignments, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 14 - UC-14 - Accept or Reject Review Invitation (Priority: P2)\n\nAllow a referee to respond to a review invitation by either accepting or rejecting it so that they can manage their review workload effectively. (Primary actor: Referee; Secondary actors: Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The referee selects a pending review invitation..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The referee‚Äôs response (accept or reject) is successfully recorded, and the system updates the review assignment status accordingly.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The referee is registered in the CMS.; The referee has received at least one review invitation.; The CMS invitation management functionality is available., **When** The referee selects a pending review invitation., **Then** The referee‚Äôs response (accept or reject) is successfully recorded, and the system updates the review assignment status accordingly.\n2. **Given** 5a**: Referee accepts the invitation but has reached the maximum review limit, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 15 - UC-15 - Access Assigned Papers (Priority: P2)\n\nAllow a referee to view and open all papers that have been assigned to them for review so they can perform the review tasks. (Primary actor: Referee; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database File Storage System; Trigger: The referee selects the option to view assigned papers after logging into the CMS..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The referee successfully views the list of assigned papers and can access the manuscript files for review.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The referee is registered in the CMS.; The referee is authenticated and logged into the CMS.; The referee has accepted at least one review invitation.; The CMS paper access functionality is available., **When** The referee selects the option to view assigned papers after logging into the CMS., **Then** The referee successfully views the list of assigned papers and can access the manuscript files for review.\n2. **Given** 4a**: No papers are currently assigned to the referee, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 16 - UC-16 - Submit Paper Review (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow a referee to submit a completed review form for an assigned paper so that the evaluation is recorded in the system and delivered to the editor. (Primary actor: Referee; Secondary actors: Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The referee selects the option to submit a review for an assigned paper..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: The completed review form is successfully stored in the CMS and made available to the editor.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The referee is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; The referee has accepted a review invitation for the paper.; The referee has access to the assigned paper.; The review form template is available in the CMS., **When** The referee selects the option to submit a review for an assigned paper., **Then** The completed review form is successfully stored in the CMS and made available to the editor.\n2. **Given** 7a**: Review form contains missing or invalid information, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 17 - UC-17 - Enforce Reviewer Workload Limit (Priority: P2)\n\nEnsure that a referee is not assigned more than five papers to review in order to maintain a manageable and fair workload. (Primary actor: Referee; Secondary actors: Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The editor attempts to assign a paper to a referee, or a referee attempts to accept a new review invitation..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The referee is assigned no more than five papers, and any attempt to exceed this limit is prevented by the system.\n\n**Accept‚Ä¶1361 tokens truncated‚Ä¶iews exist, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 22 - UC-22 - Edit Conference Schedule (Priority: P2)\n\nAllow an editor to modify the conference schedule to resolve conflicts, satisfy constraints, and finalize session details before publication. (Primary actor: Editor; Secondary actors: Administrator CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The editor selects an existing conference schedule and initiates an edit action..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The conference schedule is successfully updated and stored, with conflicts resolved and constraints satisfied.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The editor is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; A conference schedule exists (generated or previously edited).; The CMS schedule editing functionality is available., **When** The editor selects an existing conference schedule and initiates an edit action., **Then** The conference schedule is successfully updated and stored, with conflicts resolved and constraints satisfied.\n2. **Given** 6a**: Updated schedule violates constraints, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 23 - UC-23 - Generate Conference Schedule (Priority: P2)\n\nAutomatically generate a complete conference schedule that assigns accepted papers to sessions, times, and rooms in an efficient and conflict-free manner. (Primary actor: Administrator; Secondary actors: Editor CMS Scheduling Engine CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The administrator requests automatic generation of the conference schedule..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: A valid conference schedule is generated, stored, and made available for review and further editing.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The administrator is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; A set of accepted papers exists.; Required scheduling data (rooms, time slots, constraints) is available.; The CMS scheduling algorithm is available., **When** The administrator requests automatic generation of the conference schedule., **Then** A valid conference schedule is generated, stored, and made available for review and further editing.\n2. **Given** 4a**: Required scheduling data is missing or incomplete, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 24 - UC-24 - Modify Generated Conference Schedule (Priority: P2)\n\nAllow an administrator to modify an automatically generated conference schedule to accommodate real-world constraints such as room availability, presenter conflicts, or organizational requirements. (Primary actor: Administrator; Secondary actors: Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The administrator selects an existing generated conference schedule for modification..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The conference schedule is successfully modified, validated, and stored, reflecting real-world constraints.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The administrator is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; A generated conference schedule exists.; The CMS schedule editing functionality is available., **When** The administrator selects an existing generated conference schedule for modification., **Then** The conference schedule is successfully modified, validated, and stored, reflecting real-world constraints.\n2. **Given** 6a**: Modified schedule violates constraints, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 25 - UC-25 - Publish Final Conference Schedule (Priority: P2)\n\nMake the finalized conference schedule publicly available and notify all relevant stakeholders so that authors and attendees are informed of session times and locations. (Primary actor: Administrator; Secondary actors: Author Attendee Editor CMS Web Interface CMS Database Notification Service (e.g., email); Trigger: The administrator selects the option to publish the finalized conference schedule..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The final conference schedule is published and accessible, and authors and attendees are notified.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The administrator is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; A finalized and validated conference schedule exists.; The CMS publication and notification mechanisms are available., **When** The administrator selects the option to publish the finalized conference schedule., **Then** The final conference schedule is published and accessible, and authors and attendees are notified.\n2. **Given** 7a**: Notification delivery fails, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 26 - UC-26 - Register for Conference (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow an attendee to register for the conference so they can participate in conference activities. (Primary actor: Attendee; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database Payment System (external); Trigger: The attendee selects the option to register for the conference..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: The attendee is successfully registered for the conference and proceeds to payment or confirmation.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The attendee is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; Conference registration is open.; Conference pricing information is available.; The CMS registration functionality is available., **When** The attendee selects the option to register for the conference., **Then** The attendee is successfully registered for the conference and proceeds to payment or confirmation.\n2. **Given** 2a**: Attendee is not authenticated, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 27 - UC-27 - Pay Conference Registration Fee (Priority: P1)\n\nAllow an attendee to pay the conference registration fee online so that their attendance is confirmed. (Primary actor: Attendee; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database Payment System (external); Trigger: The attendee submits payment information for conference registration..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Core operational flow required for conference execution.\n\n**Independent Test**: The registration fee is successfully paid, and the attendee‚Äôs participation is confirmed.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The attendee is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; The attendee has initiated conference registration.; Conference pricing information is available.; The online payment system is available., **When** The attendee submits payment information for conference registration., **Then** The registration fee is successfully paid, and the attendee‚Äôs participation is confirmed.\n2. **Given** 7a**: Payment is declined by the payment system, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 28 - UC-28 - Receive Payment Confirmation Ticket (Priority: P2)\n\nProvide the attendee with a confirmation ticket after successful payment so that they have verifiable proof of conference registration. (Primary actor: Attendee; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database Notification Service (e.g., email); Trigger: The CMS records a successful conference registration payment..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Important supporting capability that depends on core flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The attendee receives a payment confirmation ticket that can be viewed or saved as proof of registration.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The attendee is registered and authenticated in the CMS.; The attendee has successfully completed the conference registration payment.; The CMS confirmation generation and notification mechanisms are available., **When** The CMS records a successful conference registration payment., **Then** The attendee receives a payment confirmation ticket that can be viewed or saved as proof of registration.\n2. **Given** 4a**: Notification delivery fails, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### User Story 29 - UC-29 - View Conference Schedule (Priority: P3)\n\nAllow an attendee to view the published conference schedule so they can plan which sessions to attend. (Primary actor: Attendee; Secondary actors: CMS Web Interface CMS Database; Trigger: The attendee navigates to the conference schedule page..)\n\n**Why this priority**: Supports informational access; can follow core operational flows.\n\n**Independent Test**: The attendee successfully views the published conference schedule.\n\n**Acceptance Scenarios**:\n\n1. **Given** The conference schedule has been finalized and published.; The CMS schedule viewing functionality is available.; (Optional) The attendee is authenticated, if schedule access is restricted to registered users., **When** The attendee navigates to the conference schedule page., **Then** The attendee successfully views the published conference schedule.\n2. **Given** 2a**: Attendee is not authenticated and authentication is required, **When** the actor proceeds, **Then** the system follows the defined alternative path\n\n---\n\n### Use Case Coverage *(mandatory)*\n\n- Source use cases: UC-01.md, UC-02.md, UC-03.md, UC-04.md, UC-05.md, UC-06.md, UC-07.md, UC-08.md, UC-09.md, UC-10.md, UC-11.md, UC-12.md, UC-13.md, UC-14.md, UC-15.md, UC-16.md, UC-17.md, UC-18.md, UC-19.md, UC-20.md, UC-21.md, UC-22.md, UC-23.md, UC-24.md, UC-25.md, UC-26.md, UC-27.md, UC-28.md, UC-29.md\n- Coverage map:\n- UC-01 -> User Story 1\n- UC-02 -> User Story 2\n- UC-03 -> User Story 3\n- UC-04 -> User Story 4\n- UC-05 -> User Story 5\n- UC-06 -> User Story 6\n- UC-07 -> User Story 7\n- UC-08 -> User Story 8\n- UC-09 -> User Story 9\n- UC-10 -> User Story 10\n- UC-11 -> User Story 11\n- UC-12 -> User Story 12\n- UC-13 -> User Story 13\n- UC-14 -> User Story 14\n- UC-15 -> User Story 15\n- UC-16 -> User Story 16\n- UC-17 -> User Story 17\n- UC-18 -> User Story 18\n- UC-19 -> User Story 19\n- UC-20 -> User Story 20\n- UC-21 -> User Story 21\n- UC-22 -> User Story 22\n- UC-23 -> User Story 23\n- UC-24 -> User Story 24\n- UC-25 -> User Story 25\n- UC-26 -> User Story 26\n- UC-27 -> User Story 27\n- UC-28 -> User Story 28\n- UC-29 -> User Story 29\n\n### User Acceptance Tests *(mandatory)*\n\n- UAT suite source: TC-01.md, TC-02.md, TC-03.md, TC-04.md, TC-05.md, TC-06.md, TC-07.md, TC-08.md, TC-09.md, TC-10.md, TC-11.md, TC-12.md, TC-13.md, TC-14.md, TC-15.md, TC-16.md, TC-17.md, TC-18.md, TC-19.md, TC-20.md, TC-21.md, TC-22.md, TC-23.md, TC-24.md, TC-25.md, TC-26.md, TC-27.md, TC-28.md, TC-29.md\n- UAT suite location: specs/001-uc-spec-union/uat/uat-suite.md\n\n### Edge Cases\n\n- UC-01: Public announcements are not displayed and the guest cannot view conference information.\n- UC-01: 3a**: No public announcements exist\n- UC-02: The conference registration price list is not displayed and the guest cannot view pricing information.\n- UC-02: 4a**: Registration price list is not available\n- UC-03: The conference schedule is not displayed and the guest cannot view session information.\n- UC-03: 4a**: Conference schedule has not been published\n- UC-04: The user account is not created, and the user remains unregistered.\n- UC-04: 6a**: Email format is invalid\n- UC-05: The registration information is found to be invalid, and the user account is not created.\n- UC-05: 3a**: Email format is invalid\n- UC-06: The user is not authenticated and cannot access protected CMS features.\n- UC-06: 5a**: Username or password is incorrect\n- UC-07: The user‚Äôs password is not changed, and the original password remains valid.\n- UC-08: The paper manuscript is not submitted, and no incomplete or invalid submission is recorded as final.\n- UC-08: 5a**: Uploaded file format is not supported\n- UC-09: The manuscript file is not stored, and no invalid or non-compliant file is associated with the submission.\n- UC-09: 5a**: File format is not supported\n- UC-10: The submission progress is not saved, and newly entered information is not retained.\n- UC-10: 3a**: Submission data contains invalid or incomplete values\n- UC-11: The author does not receive or cannot view the final decision for the paper.\n- UC-11: 3a**: Notification delivery fails\n- UC-12: The author does not receive or cannot view the presentation schedule for their accepted paper.\n- UC-12: 3a**: Notification delivery fails\n- UC-13: The referee does not receive or cannot view the review invitation.\n- UC-13: 3a**: Referee has reached the maximum allowed number of review assignments\n- UC-14: The referee‚Äôs response is not recorded, and the review invitation remains unresolved.\n- UC-14: 5a**: Referee accepts the invitation but has reached the maximum review limit\n- UC-15: The referee cannot view or access the papers assigned to them.\n- UC-15: 4a**: No papers are currently assigned to the referee\n- UC-16: The review form is not submitted, and the editor does not receive the referee‚Äôs evaluation.\n- UC-16: 7a**: Review form contains missing or invalid information\n- UC-17: The referee is assigned more than five papers, resulting in an unreasonable workload (constraint violation).\n- UC-17: 3a**: Assigning the paper would exceed the maximum of five papers\n- UC-18: Referees are not assigned to the paper, and the paper remains without sufficient reviewers.\n- UC-18: 6a**: Selected referee has reached the maximum review workload\n- UC-19: The paper has fewer than or more than three referees assigned, preventing fair and consistent review.\n- UC-19: 4a**: Fewer than three referees are assigned\n- UC-20: The editor cannot access one or more completed review forms, preventing proper evaluation of the paper.\n- UC-20: 1a**: Review form submission is incomplete or invalid\n- UC-21: The decision is not recorded or communicated, leaving the paper without an official outcome.\n- UC-21: 7a**: Fewer than three completed reviews exist\n- UC-22: The conference schedule is not updated, and unresolved conflicts remain.\n- UC-22: 6a**: Updated schedule violates constraints\n- UC-23: The conference schedule is not generated due to errors, missing data, or violated constraints.\n- UC-23: 4a**: Required scheduling data is missing or incomplete\n- UC-24: The conference schedule is not modified, and real-world constraints remain unresolved.\n- UC-24: 6a**: Modified schedule violates constraints\n- UC-25: The conference schedule is not published or notifications are not delivered, leaving users uninformed.\n- UC-25: 7a**: Notification delivery fails\n- UC-26: The attendee is not registered for the conference.\n- UC-26: 2a**: Attendee is not authenticated\n- UC-27: The payment is not completed, and the attendee‚Äôs registration remains unconfirmed.\n- UC-27: 7a**: Payment is declined by the payment system\n- UC-28: The attendee does not receive or cannot access the payment confirmation ticket.\n- UC-28: 4a**: Notification delivery fails\n- UC-29: The attendee cannot view the conference schedule.\n- UC-29: 2a**: Attendee is not authenticated and authentication is required\n\n### Security & Privacy Considerations *(mandatory for features touching data or roles)*\n\n- Data classification: confidential/PII (accounts, submissions, reviews, payments)\n- Roles and access checks: guest, author, reviewer, chair, admin, attendee must only access permitted actions\n- Logging exclusions: credentials, payment details, review content marked confidential\n\n## Requirements *(mandatory)*\n\n### Functional Requirements\n\n- **FR-001**: System MUST support view public announcements as defined in UC-01\n- **FR-002**: System MUST support view conference registration prices as defined in UC-02\n- **FR-003**: System MUST support view conference schedule as defined in UC-03\n- **FR-004**: System MUST support register user account as defined in UC-04\n- **FR-005**: System MUST support validate registration information as defined in UC-05\n- **FR-006**: System MUST support log in to system as defined in UC-06\n- **FR-007**: System MUST support change password as defined in UC-07\n- **FR-008**: System MUST support submit paper manuscript as defined in UC-08\n- **FR-009**: System MUST support upload manuscript file as defined in UC-09\n- **FR-010**: System MUST support save submission progress as defined in UC-10\n- **FR-011**: System MUST support receive paper decision as defined in UC-11\n- **FR-012**: System MUST support receive presentation schedule as defined in UC-12\n- **FR-013**: System MUST support receive review invitation as defined in UC-13\n- **FR-014**: System MUST support accept or reject review invitation as defined in UC-14\n- **FR-015**: System MUST support access assigned papers as defined in UC-15\n- **FR-016**: System MUST support submit paper review as defined in UC-16\n- **FR-017**: System MUST support enforce reviewer workload limit as defined in UC-17\n- **FR-018**: System MUST support assign referees to submitted papers as defined in UC-18\n- **FR-019**: System MUST support ensure three reviewers per paper as defined in UC-19\n- **FR-020**: System MUST support receive completed review forms as defined in UC-20\n- **FR-021**: System MUST support make final paper decision as defined in UC-21\n- **FR-022**: System MUST support edit conference schedule as defined in UC-22\n- **FR-023**: System MUST support generate conference schedule as defined in UC-23\n- **FR-024**: System MUST support modify generated conference schedule as defined in UC-24\n- **FR-025**: System MUST support publish final conference schedule as defined in UC-25\n- **FR-026**: System MUST support register for conference as defined in UC-26\n- **FR-027**: System MUST support pay conference registration fee as defined in UC-27\n- **FR-028**: System MUST support receive payment confirmation ticket as defined in UC-28\n- **FR-029**: System MUST support view conference schedule as defined in UC-29\n\n### Key Entities *(include if feature involves data)*\n\n- **User Account**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Role**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Announcement**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Registration Price**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Schedule**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Submission**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Manuscript File**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Review Invitation**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Review**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Decision**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Conference Registration**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Payment**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n- **Confirmation Ticket**: Core record required to fulfill related use cases\n\n## Success Criteria *(mandatory)*\n\n### Measurable Outcomes\n\n- **SC-001**: 100% of UC-XX use cases are represented by at least one user story with acceptance scenarios\n- **SC-002**: Unified UAT suite includes all acceptance tests from TC-XX.md and passes before release\n- **SC-003**: 95% of primary user journeys complete without error in user testing\n- **SC-004**: Average user completes core flows (register, submit, review, register/pay) in under 5 minutes per flow\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- UC-XX.md use cases must remain available as the source of truth\n- TC-XX.md acceptance tests must remain available to assemble the unified UAT suite\n\n## Assumptions\n\n- UC-XX.md and TC-XX.md are the authoritative sources for functional scope and acceptance tests\n- All use cases are in scope for this specification\n- Standard web application usability expectations apply\n"}}
